callr::r()

is your friend.

[see_image_2] So for the above question, `C=3`, `B=2`, `A=1`. At the first execution, `f` returns `1` and also updates `x` in global environment to `1`. Similary for the subsequent executions, `x` gets updated globablly with an #RStats #DataScience [TimeStamp:17112021220047] https://t.co/PooUcn246P

it doesn‚Äôt find the variable, it will create the variable in global environment. See for example below: I have defined a function `f` with a variable `y` in it to which I have assigned 1. If I try to access `y` outside function, I #RStats #DataScience [TimeStamp:17112021220047]
increment 1. [see_image_3] In contrast, if I use `<-`, I would get `A=B=C=1`. [see_image_4] #RStats #DataScience [TimeStamp:17112021220047] https://t.co/iUGTBpon4W

Super assignment operator `<<-`can be used for assignment in parent environment. Which of the following is TRUE for the following code? [see_image_1] #RStats #DataScience [TimeStamp:17112021123050] https://t.co/v10ouH0oVT

Correct Ans: C > B > A. `<<-` is known as super assignment operator. In contrast to the regular assignment operator `<-` which does the assignment in current environment, `<<-` does the assignment in parent environment. If in case #RStats #DataScience [TimeStamp:17112021220047]

get the error, as `y` doesn‚Äôt exist in global environment. It only exists in `f`‚Äôs environment. [see_image_1] But if I rewrite the above code using `<<-`, I don't get any error. `y` is now defined in global environment. #RStats #DataScience [TimeStamp:17112021220047] https://t.co/1y0HDvAP2q
